See Also
Encephalitis, tick-borne - Kyrgyzstan 2000.2799

Date: Fri, 30 Jun 2000 06:41:26 +0300
From: Stephen Berger <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>


The following background information on tick-borne encephalitis in the
former Russian republics was abstracted from GIDEON http://www.cyinfo.com

: [edited

Russian Spring-Summer [Encephalitis - RSSE (Eastern) form:
The disease was first described during the 1930's among residents of the
taiga forests. Disease rates peak in Autumn in the European region; and
during Spring and Summer in the Eastern region. Currently urban dwellers
account for 68% of patients, and forest workers for 15% to 20%.

The disease is endemic to Russia (80% of USSR cases), Ukraine, Beylorussia,
Kazakhstan, Kirgyzia [Kyrgystan, Lithuania, Latvia, Estonia, Moldova,
Uzbekistan and Azerbaijan.

--
Stephen Berger
<mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
